answers.body_markdown:
When you have both an entrypoint and a command (whether they come from the `Dockerfile`, `docker-compose.yml`, or `docker run` arguments) they get combined together into one command line.  In your case, this runs (quotes added)

&lt;!-- language: lang-sh --&gt;

    bash -c &quot;/opt/app/wait-for-it-and-start.sh&quot; &quot;$$MONGO_HOST:$$MONGO_PORT&quot;

If you look at [the bash manual](https://www.gnu.org/software/bash/manual/html_node/Invoking-Bash.html), the first parameter after the text to evaluate is taken as the implicit `$0` parameter that normally holds the name of the script, which is why it&#39;s getting swallowed here.

The easiest mechanical change is to just remove the `sh -c` wrapper.  (You almost never need it, unless you need things like redirection or command chaining, and if you do, the plain-string form of _e.g._ `CMD` will insert it for you.)

&lt;!-- language: lang-sh --&gt;

    ENTRYPOINT [&quot;/opt/app/wait-for-it-and-start.sh&quot;]

I suspect you&#39;re counting on the shell to expand the environment variables for you here.  It&#39;s hard to make that happen with this sequence (there&#39;s nowhere you can actually insert the `sh -c` wrapper that works).  It would be easier to just use the environment variables directly in your script than to try to read them back as positional parameters.  For example

&lt;!-- language: lang-sh --&gt;

    #!/bin/sh
    wait-for-it.sh &quot;$MONGO_HOST:$MONGO_PORT&quot;
    exec &quot;$@&quot;

with the corresponding Dockerfile

&lt;!-- language: lang-sh --&gt;

    ...
    ENTRYPOINT [&quot;/opt/app/wait-for-it-and-start.sh&quot;]
    CMD [&quot;/opt/app/myapp&quot;]

